      "writtenOn": "2020-03-13T14:37:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Not a silly question. At the moment, every call to Write() results in a separate log entry being sent to cloud logging: https://skia.googlesource.com/buildbot/+/master/task_driver/go/td/receiver.go#347  Each entry becomes its own BigTable row, and it\u0027s inefficient to have a bunch of rows which only contain newlines.  I thought about buffering until we see a newline and then writing one entry per line, but I was concerned about the possibility of missing partial log output in the case of a crash.\n\nSemi-related, there are currently some (probably incorrect) assumptions that each log entry represents at least one full line (eg. https://skia.googlesource.com/buildbot/+/master/task_driver/go/task-driver-server/main.go#78\n\nLong term, I think the right move is just to have task drivers write structured data to stdout (or a file), including log streams, and have some wrapper process take care of getting the data into Cloud Logs or BigTable or wherever. That would have a few benefits:\n- There\u0027s more insulation against crashes.\n- Task drivers don\u0027t need to auth to Cloud Logging.\n- Task drivers could be a little leaner since they could just dump output and move on.\n- Nested task drivers could be handled trivially, as long as the wrapper sees all of the log output.",
      "parentUuid": "4c3a4379_1fb9efd6",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 137,
        "startChar": 23,
        "endLine": 137,
